content.description: Boulder start to 10+ climbing. Just gets easier. Stick clip start might be a good idea.
content.location: To the Right of Rodeo Drive

content.description: the very next climb left of ticks for chicks. harder bottom to easy pockets. 3 or 4 bolts, two bolt anchor.
Climbed without using the flake at the top.
content.location: In the corner to the right of Rooster Cogburn.

content.description: About 50 feet right of Pronghorn Pinnacle. Climb face on left side of large dihedral, using good flake for the first three clips, until flake ends. Clip one more bolt and head for anchor on slabbier terrain.  Hardest at first move.
content.protection: 4 bolts plus rap rings for anchor.
content.location: The climb is right of the hanging tree and left of a chimney feature. It climbes a face with a flake system on the left that ends 3/4 the way up.

content.description:
Start at the base of the crack on the detached block to the right of the Duke. Stem on the frontside of the crack and then work your way into the backside of crack. Move through a few bulges until you get to the roof. Pull through the roof and climb the face to the anchors. Enjoy the view. This route was originally climbed

onsight on gear.
content.location: Rodeo wall. To right of the duke and left of western grip.

content.description: Start on thin holds below the bulge and climb onto the slabby face. Commit upwards on pockets and crimps towards the anchors.
content.location: At rodeo drive. Between the solace of bolted faces and John Wayne.

content.description: Thin is the best word to describe this route.  Starts by pulling a small bulge and then vertical climbing on crimps and shallow pockets takes you to the anchor.  The "Lander Sport Climbs" guide by Steve Bechtel rates this 5.12a but I didn't think it was quite that hard.  But maybe if your shorter...
content.protection: 5 or 6 bolts to a two bolt anchor.
content.location: This route is to the right of Rodeo Drive just around the corner.

content.description:
Brand new May 25, 2020

Hard bit right off the ground getting to second bolt, then quite cruiser. I cleaned the face and climbed mostly using face holds, but I am sure many will choose to climb the flake features to the right.

Pro tip: can be cleaned when lowering from Dirty Sally. Safer and more efficient, if you happen to be doing both.
content.location: A few feet right of Dirty Sally. Start with obvious flake chockstone in the flake

content.description: 3 boulder problems with the one going to the anchors being the crux. Great movement and well bolted.
Difficult climbing on small holds through the first couple bolts leads to easier climbing up high.
content.location: 2 ways to find this, 1 - walk out free camping road looking for the engraved sign “Rodeo Drive Area” on left, 2 - Walk way out right along the cliff band until the the last group of bolted routes then back track as of 2018 it’s the 5th route from the end of the OK Corral.  It’s on the nice flat pocked panel to the right of Rooster Cogburn.  3rd climb from left starting at the crack/chimney/break on this flat panel.  A tip is its the one that doesn’t look like a 5.10 start.

content.description: Starts on a large flake, then continues left up a crack/face system, just right of the arete, to chains.
content.location: This is the leftmost route on the face right of the gully and pillar that contains Western Grip. Starts on a large flake and trends left. Shares start with Imagine What I Could Do to Your Face.

content.description: Fun Retro-Bolt of a chopped route. Good pockets and consistent climbing. Avoid choss rock right of route.
content.location: Right of Ticks or For Chicks and left of Dirty Sally. First bolt really close to ground.

content.description:
This takes the right leaning prow across the gully from Drinking Dry Clouds. An easy start quickly leads into the technical crux near the second bolt. Continue on long pulls between small holds through four more bolts to the chains. Most of the moves could prove to be redpoint cruxes. The technical, bouldery, and continuously low-percentage movement makes this a well earned route.

This faces SSE and gets PM shade.

The 2011 guide gives it 13b and the 2015 guide says 12d.
content.protection: 6 draws + anchors (which had carabiners 08/15) and don't blow the second clip.
content.location: Around the corner and right of the Solace of Bolted Faces and left of Drinking Dry Clouds.

climbs.name: Imagine What I Could Do to Your Face

content.description: Starts on top of a large flake, with a low first clip.  Commit to the face (right) and follow pockets to the top.
content.location: This is the second bolt line you encounter (left to right) on the pocketed face right of the gully and pillar that contains Western Grip.  Starts on a large flake and trends right onto the face.  Shares a start with Rio Bravo to the left.

content.description: The route immediately right of Rooster Cogburn.  This route has two obvious flakes with a powerful compression sequence in the middle.
Four bolts of bouldery climbing over a bulge on neat pockets and holds
content.location: Furthest right wall on the at the OK corral

content.protection:
6 bolts to ring anchors

Update 6/10/18

9 glue-in bolts to glue-in anchors with "clip and lower" hooks.

Please TR and lower on your own carabiners. The permanent anchors should be used to lower from only once per climbing party to make them last as long as possible.
content.location: Right of Ride Me Cowgirl and left of Short Pony

content.description: Climb the obvious dihedral crack, on the far right end of rodeo drive, up to the horizontal break. Sketchy Traverse right to anchors on southern draw.
content.protection: Single rack. Maybe double 3” if climber choose. Sketchy Traverse right and down climb to anchors at Southern Draw.
content.location: Obvious crack on the far right end of rodeo drive to the right of the solace of bolted faces and left of Southern Draw.

content.description: two routes right of ticks for chicks
Slightly over-bolted at the start, this intricate route follows a surprisingly beta-intensive path through pockets and crimps to a slightly overhanging headwall.
content.protection: 6 bolts to fixe rings.  The first bolt is easily clipped from the ground, but they're all pretty close together.  Watch for Z-clip on the 4th bolt!
content.location: Two routes right of Ticks For Chicks.  Starts from the extreme right edge of a 3-4 foot tall ledge.  Look for a rock scar about 6 feet up that's shaped a little bit like Wisconsin, with 2 bolts on its left side.

pathTokens: 3. Right Side (Diamonds, La Vaca, Pronghorn, Rodeo Drive)
